<font color="#FF0000">LANGUAGE</font><br>
<tt>Thu Jan 30 17:01:44 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Language is definitely a powerful tool/force.  This occasionally includes explitives.  As a radioman, I did learn not to use certain words on the airwaves, though at certain times, under certain stresses, they would slip out.  They still do.  I will take Joe and John's cautions and concerns to heart.  In my defense (defensive?  who? Me?), I would merely point out that none of my explitives were directed at anyone except me.<br>
Beyond language, it might be good to examine these emotions that we are expressing in various ways on this site.  I certainly feel very strongly about 'Nam, lessons learned or not learned, etc.  Just let me hear the word &quot;Vietnam&quot; - on the TV, in overheard conversation, anywhere, and I experience a &quot;rush&quot; of emotions, mostly painful but some that are more positive (I can't go so far as to call them &quot;joyful&quot;).  In any case, my response is often to let these out, in one form or another, sometimes inappropriately.  How do other vets respond?
<p><code>-- miketol@mtco.com  (Mike Toliver) </code><p>


